''Time'' is in the Chicago Park District, in the Washington Park community area on Chicago's South Side, near to the Midway Plaisance. This location, within generally poor neighborhoods largely indifferent to works of art,<ref name=UFSTIaAA>{{cite web
|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CTRB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0FF7872C938CF271&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420
|title=Unfortunately For Sculptor Taft, Indifference and Austerity Are - Formidable Foes of Posterity
|accessdate=2009-01-24
|date=1989-06-18
|publisher=[[Newsbank]]
|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]
|author=Granger, Bob}}</ref> makes the sculpture a contributing structure to the Washington Park federal [[Historic_district_(United_States)#Federal-level|Registered Historic District]], listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].<ref name=NRoHPRFWP>{{cite web|url=http://gis.hpa.state.il.us/hargis/PDFs/223353.pdf|title=National Register of Historic Places Registration Form: Washington Park|accessdate=2009-04-01|date=2004-07-02|format=PDF|publisher=[[United States Department of the Interior]]/[[National Park Service]]|author=Bachrach, Julia Sniderman}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.historicdistricts.com/IL/Cook/districts.html|title=Illinois  - Cook County  - Historic Districts|accessdate=2009-04-01|publisher=[[National Register of Historic Places]]}}</ref>  ''Time'' is considered to be the most important piece of monumental art in the Park District, which hosts over 100 art works.<ref name=PAFOLOP>{{cite web
|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CSTB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EB4217A9AEFA578&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420
|title=Park Advocates Fret Over Limits On Preservation
|accessdate=2009-01-24
|date=1994-01-11
|publisher=[[Newsbank]]
|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]
|author=Drell, Adrienne}}</ref><ref name=UFSTIaAA/> Its importance stems from its sculptor, its message, the era in which it was created,<ref name=MNTTOFT/>  and the design of its [[reflecting pool]] by [[Howard Van Doren Shaw]].<ref name=G166/><ref name=timeout>{{cite web|url=http://www.timeout.com/chicago/articles/features/12067/40-outdoor-artworks-we-love-31-40|title=40 outdoor artworks we love (31<U+2013>40): Historic, modern, quirky or just unassailably iconic<U+2014>these paragons of public art turn the entire city into a museum|accessdate=2009-01-24|date=July 28 &ndash; August 3, 2005|publisher=[[Time Out (company)|Time Out]]|work=Time Out Chicago|author=Ferrara, Annette, Kathryn Hixson, Craig Keller, Ruth Lopez, Madeline Nusser, Sean O'Connor, Jerry Pohlen, Judy Sutton Taylor and Josh Tyson}}</ref> Robert Jones, director of design and construction for the [[Art Institute of Chicago]] at the time, stated in 1999 that ''Time'' was the first finished art piece to be made of any type of concrete.<ref name=FFTBC/> 

The sculpture is located a few blocks from Taft's studio, the [[Lorado Taft Midway Studios]], now a [[Chicago Landmark]] and [[National Historic Landmark]], located at 60th Street and Ingleside Avenue.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ci.chi.il.us/Landmarks/T/TaftMidway.html|title=Lorado Taft's Midway Studios|accessdate=2009-03-06|publisher=City of Chicago Department of Planning and Development, Landmarks Division|year=2003}}</ref> Other notable sculptures nearby include [[Henry Moore]]'s National Historic Landmark ''[[Nuclear Energy (Henry Moore sculpture)|Nuclear Energy]]'', which is on the site of the [[Chicago Pile-1|first self-sustaining nuclear reaction]] at the [[University of Chicago]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tps.cr.nps.gov/nhl/detail.cfm?ResourceId=204&ResourceType=Site|title=Site of the First Self-Sustaining Nuclear Reaction |accessdate=2009-03-06|publisher=[[National Park Service]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://webapps.cityofchicago.org/LandmarksWeb/landmarkDetail.do;jsessionid=L1HTcBF85WsbdWR58fFGQFc44K2Tvqsn6LxTV7jQbxM1Ymnl84FG!941869876?lanID=1383|title=Site of the First Self-Sustaining Controlled Nuclear Chain Reaction|accessdate=2009-03-06|publisher=City of Chicago Department of Planning and Development, Landmarks Division}}</ref>  Jackson Park, connected to Washington Park and ''Time'' by the Midway Plaisance, hosts the Chicago Landmark [[Statue of the Republic]];<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ci.chi.il.us/Landmarks/S/StatueRepublic.html|title=Statue of The Republic|accessdate=2009-03-06|publisher=City of Chicago Department of Planning and Development, Landmarks Division|year=2003}}</ref> at one time the Midway Plaisance, Jackson Park and Washington Park were jointly known as "South Park".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.encyclopedia.chicagohistory.org/pages/955.html|title=Park Districts|accessdate=2009-03-06|year=2005|author=Bachrach, Julia Sniderman|work=The Electronic Encyclopedia of Chicago|publisher=[[Chicago Historical Society]]}}</ref>

There is little agreement on the dimensions of ''Time'', with various sources describing it as between {{convert|102|to|127|ft|m|1}} long.<ref name=TFoTGTCT/><ref name=UFSTIaAA/><ref name=MNTTOFT/> One of the few precise estimates describes it as {{convert|126|ft|10|in|m|1}} long, {{convert|23|ft|6|in|m|1}} wide and {{convert|24|ft|m|1}} tall.<ref name=Rtrot/>  The sources are often unclear about whether they are describing the width of the reflecting pool from exterior wall to exterior wall, the width of the water within the reflecting pool's interior walls, the width of the base of the sculpted mass of humanity, the width of the sculpted masses themselves, or the width of the [[Lot (real estate)|parcel]] of land upon which ''Time'' is built.

Water began running in the completed sculpture on September 1, 1920,<ref name=TFoT/> although it was not dedicated to the city until November 15, 1922.<ref name=TFoTGTCT/> [[University of Chicago]] President [[Harry Pratt Judson]] delivered an address at the dedication ceremony at the Midway Plaisance, before contributions from Taft. President of the B.F. Ferguson Trust Charles Hutchinson, and John Barton Payne, President of the South Park Board.<ref name=TFoTGTCT/><ref>{{cite news|title=Dedicate Taft Work At Midway On Wednesday|work=Chicago Daily Tribune|page=15|date=1922-11-12}}</ref>

{{anchor|Design and realisation}}
==Design and realization==
{{multiple image
 | align     = right
 | direction = vertical
 | header    = Post-restoration ''Fountain of Time''
 | header_align = left/right/center
 | header_background = 
 | footer    = 
 | footer_align = left/right/center
 | footer_background = 
 | width     = 
 | image1    = Fountain of Time full front.jpg
 | width1    = 190
 | caption1  = View from the east
 | image2    = Fountain of Time front3.jpg
 | width2    = 190
 | caption2  = View of mass of humanity from the front of the middle south portion
}}
The sculpture is made of a form of [[Hollow casting|hollow-cast]] [[concrete]], reinforced with [[steel]]. It was cast in a 4,500-piece [[Mold (manufacturing)|mold]],<ref name=AGtC/> using {{convert|250|ST|t|lk=on}} of a material described as "concrete-like", which incorporated [[pebble]]s from the [[Potomac River]].<ref name=TFoTGTCT/> This composite material was an innovation at the time. For years, John Early of Washington, DC, had used materials that seemed durable in the face of elements such as the weather and urban soot and grime.<ref name=APaP/> He had determined that by adding crushed pebbles he could create a new concrete mixture more durable than [[limestone]] but cheaper than marble or [[bronze]].<ref name=APaP>{{cite web|url=http://query.nytimes.com/mem/archive-free/pdf?res=9A06E6DA1E39E133A25755C2A9679D946395D6CF|title=Art: Pictures and Print|accessdate=2009-01-24|date=1922-11-26|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|work=[[The New York Times]] | format=PDF}}</ref>  The reflection from the [[silica]] of the crushed stones complemented the durability with artistic beauty; the same material was used at Chicago's [[Fine Arts Building (Chicago)|Fine Arts Building]].<ref name=APaP/>

The sculpture depicts a hooded [[Father Time]] carrying a [[scythe]],<ref>{{cite web
|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CTRB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0FF686576576840D&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420
|title=Hyde Park Full of Architectural, Art Gems|accessdate=2009-01-24|date=1987-05-20|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=Chicago Tribune|author=Uslan, A.F.}}</ref> and watching over a parade of 100 figures arranged in an [[ellipse]], with an overall [[pyramid]]al geometry. The [[allegory|allegorical]] procession depicts the entire spectrum of humanity at various stages of life.<ref name=ACOBS/><ref name=MNTTOFT/><ref name=TFoT/>  The contemporary 1920s ''[[Chicago Daily Tribune]]'' described the figures as "heroic",<ref name=TFoT/><ref name=T>{{cite news|title=Time|work=Chicago Daily Tribune|page=4|date=1920-08-25}}</ref><ref name=LToMS>{{cite news|title=Lorado Taft on Modern Sculpture|work=Chicago Daily Tribune|page=7|date=1921-07-30|author=Peattie, Elia W.}}</ref> and that choice of adjective has stayed with the piece.<ref name=UFSTIaAA/> The figures are said to be passing in review as they rush through the stages of life,<ref name=TFoT2/> and include soldiers, frolicking children and kissing couples.<ref name=timeout/> Father Time is described in various newspaper articles as "huge", "weird", and "dominant".<ref name=T/>  Other ''Tribune'' critics described ''Time'' as a "pet atrocity" of Taft in large part due to its ugliness.  One critic described the white figures as reminiscent of false teeth smiling across the end of the Midway.<ref name=G173>Garvey, p. 173.</ref>

''Time'' commemorates the first 100 years of peace between the United States and Great Britain after the [[Treaty of Ghent]] concluded the [[War of 1812]] on December 24, 1814.<ref name=AGtC/> The design was inspired by the poem "Paradox of Time" by [[Henry Austin Dobson]]:<ref name=FoT2>{{cite web|url=http://www.cpdit01.com/resources/fountain_of_time.cfm|title=Fountain of Time|accessdate=2009-01-24|year=2007|publisher=[[Chicago Park District]]}}</ref> "Time goes, you say? Ah no, Alas, time stays, we go".<ref name=AGtC/><ref name=TFoT>{{cite news|title=''Time'' of Time|work=Chicago Daily Tribune|page=2|date=1920-09-02}}</ref><ref name=TFoT2>{{cite news|title=''Time'' of Time|work=Chicago Daily Tribune|page=17|date=1921-08-11}}</ref> ''Time'''s theme has been compared to [[William Shakespeare|Shakespeare]]'s [[All the world's a stage]] monologue in ''[[As You Like It]]'', which describes the seven ages of man: infant, schoolboy, lover, soldier, justice, old age, and dementia.<ref name=TFoT2/> Taft's figures represent birth, the struggle for existence, love, family life, religion, poetry, and war.<ref name=Csstmo/>

Although most of the figures are generic representations of human forms in various walks and stages of life, Taft included himself, with one of his assistants following him, along the west side of the sculpture. He is portrayed wearing a smock, with his head bowed and hands clasped behind his back.<ref name=AGtC/><ref name=MNTTOFT/> His daughters served as models for some of the figures.<ref name=FoTMWFaM/>

Taft is now better remembered for his books, such as ''The History of American Sculpture'' (1903), regarded as the first comprehensive work on the subject. However, in his day he was well-known for [[portrait]]s and allegorical public sculpture, of which ''Fountain of Time'' is a prime example.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Oxford Dictionary of Art|page=549|isbn=0198600844|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|year=1997|editor=Chilvers, Ian, Harold Osborne and Dennis Farr|edition=New}}</ref> It was produced in the period following his assignment to design sculptures for [[William Le Baron Jenney]]'s 1893 Horticultural Building for the [[World's Columbian Exposition]].  During this period he designed several large-scale public works, including ''Fountain of the Great Lakes''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.encyclopedia.chicagohistory.org/pages/1723.html|title=Lorado Taft and Chicago Sculpture|accessdate=2009-01-23|year=2005|publisher=[[Chicago Historical Society]]|work=The Electronic Encyclopedia of Chicago|author=Garvey, Timothy J.}}</ref> Taft resided in [[Illinois]] for most of his life, and from 1906 worked in the [[Lorado Taft Midway Studios|Midway Studios]],<ref name=ft>{{cite web
|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:PJSB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0F8C56090C8361C9&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420
|title=fighting time -- Elmwood native's sculpture in Chicago park now restored, but water element of ' Fountain of Time ' awaits renewal|accessdate=2009-01-24|date=2003-01-19|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Peoria Journal Star]]|author=Ramsey, Mike}}</ref> starting in 1906.<ref>Taft, p. 28.</ref>

==Restoration==
{{multiple image
 | align     = left
 | direction = horizontal
 | header    = Lorado Taft self-portrait
 | header_align = left/right/center
 | header_background = 
 | footer    = A self-depiction of the fountain sculptor, [[Lorado Taft]], that is among the mass of humanity is shown before (left) and after (right) restoration.
 | footer_align = left/right/center
 | footer_background = 
 | width     = 
 | image1    = LTFountainOfTime2.jpg
 | width1    = 115
 | caption1  = 
 | image2    = Fountain of Time Lorado Taft face.jpg
 | width2    = 128
 | caption2  = }}
Designed without [[expansion joints]], ''Time'' is one of a small number of outdoor sculptures made of reinforced pebble/concrete aggregate, few of which have been created since the 1930s.<ref name=MNTTOFT/> In 1936, ''Time'''s weather-related cracks were repaired; further work occurred in 1955. The sculpture's subsequent repairs were followed by a rededication celebration in 1966. Although the sculpture received regular maintenance, early repair crews often did more harm than good, by using techniques such as [[sandblasting]] and patching cracks with rigid materials.<ref name=FFTBC/><ref name=MNTTOFT/>

By the 1980s the sculpture was crumbling; cracks had developed, details of the figures had worn away, and moisture had eroded the internal structure.<ref name=MNTTOFT/> In wintertime the fountain had to be protected by a [[Tarpaulin|tarp]].<ref name=Csstmo>{{cite web
|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CSTB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EB3732F9E16DC28&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420
|title=Chicagoan's sculpture shows time marches on|accessdate=2009-01-24|date=1991-01-20|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Rotenberk, Lori}}</ref> Weather, [[air pollution]], and vandalism meant that hundreds of thousands of dollars were now needed for restoration.<ref name=UFSTIaAA/><ref name=HPlvfrf/>
The Chicago Park District, [[University of Chicago]], and [[Art Institute of Chicago]] conservators all sponsored restoration work,<ref name=HPlvfrf/><ref>{{cite web
|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CSTB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EB3732F8444A69F&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Metro Briefings|accessdate=2009-01-24|date=1991-01-20|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]}}</ref> including drying out the cavity of the hollow sculpture, removal of the deteriorated substructure, a newly designed ventilation system within the piece, a protective exterior coating, and repairs to the reflecting pool.<ref name=HPlvfrf/><ref name=Csstmo/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www-news.uchicago.edu/releases/05/050915.davis.shtml|title=Garden honoring memory of Dr. Allison Davis, University of Chicago social anthropologist, to be dedicated Saturday, September 17 |accessdate=2009-01-24|date=2005-09-15|publisher=[[University of Chicago]] News Office|author=Harms, William}}</ref> In 1989 Chicago Park District allocated $150,000 to the repair project, which amount was matched by the Ferguson fund.<ref name=FoTMWFaM>{{cite web|url=http://infoweb.newsbank.com/iw-search/we/InfoWeb?p_action=doc&p_topdoc=1&p_docnum=1&p_sort=YMD_date:D&p_product=NewsBank&p_text_direct-0=document_id=(%200EB4217BD77C09FD%20)&p_docid=0EB4217BD77C09FD&p_theme=aggregated5&p_queryname=0EB4217BD77C09FD&f_openurl=yes&p_nbid=X54F52MOMTIzNjMwNTI2MS4zMzk5OTQ6MToxMDoxMjguMTIuMC4w&|title=Fountain of Time- Masterpiece With Family as Models|accessdate=2009-01-24|date=1994-01-16|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Drell, Adrienne}}</ref>  By the end of 1991, the Park District had collected $320,000 of the $520,000 estimated repair costs from public and private funds,<ref>{{cite web
|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CSTB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EB37385D4DAF909&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420
|title=Donors, volunteers are needed|accessdate=2009-01-24|date=1991-12-30|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Siewers, Alf}}</ref> although in 1994 the sculpture still awaited repair.<ref name=FoTMWFaM/>
{{multiple image
 | align     = right
 | direction = horizontal
 | header    = Father Time
 | header_align = left/right/center
 | header_background = 
 | footer    = [[Father Time]] stands at the eastern edge of the fountain, shown before (left) and after (right) restoration.
 | footer_align = left/right/center
 | footer_background = 
