 | width2    = 115
 | caption2  = 
}}
By early 1997, after almost two decades of activity, the only repairs completed were phase one of the air ventilation system to dehumidify the hollow base, the drainage pipes and a new inner roof.<ref name=MNTTOFT>{{cite web
|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CTRB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EB42880D15CB2E5&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420
|title=Mother Nature Takes Toll On Father Time|accessdate=2009-01-24|date=1997-06-19|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=Chicago Tribune|author=Newbart, Dave}}</ref> Plans now included the erection of a temporary two-story metal building to protect all but the giant Father Time from the harsh winters and to facilitate year-round repair; the reinforcement of corroded steel interior portions; the replacement of inconsistent patches; the substitution of engineered spacing for natural cracks, and finally, hand-brushed concrete recoating.<ref name=MNTTOFT/> The temporary building was budgeted at $270,000; the city spent a total of $450,000 on repairs approved by the Park District that year.<ref name=MNTTOFT/><ref>{{cite web
|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CTRB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EB429869FFB0873&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420
|title=Chicago's Flamingo In The Pink - The Federal Government Goes To Bat With Paint And Rust Removers To Restore Two Of Chicago's Most Prominent, If Not Exactly Beloved, Outdoor Sculptures, Alexander Calder's and Claes Oldenburg's "Batcolumn."|accessdate=2009-01-24|date=1998-06-25|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=Chicago Tribune|author=Mendell, David}}</ref>

On April 19, 1999, the $1.6&nbsp;million, two-year phase two restoration began, scheduled for completion by May 2001.<ref name=FFTBC>{{cite web|
url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CTRB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EB42A64CB3B0261&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420
|title=Fountain Face-Lift Turns Back Clock - The Elements Have Been Hard On Lorado Taft's Fountain Of Time In Washington Park. But Crews Hope To Restore Its Splendor.|accessdate=2009-01-24|date=1999-05-25|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=Chicago Tribune|author=Deering, Tara}}</ref><ref name=AvpsuttM>{{cite web
|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CSTB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EB4240CF419219E&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420
|title=A visiting princess steps up to the Mike|accessdate=2009-01-24|date=1999-04-19|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Sneed, Michael}}</ref> Five workers began repairing the cracks, killing biological growth, removing [[calcium]] deposits and pollution-blackened [[gypsum]], and coating the {{convert|10000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} surface with a combination of lime putty, [[adobe]] cement and sand. The inoperable reflecting pool was not repaired in this phase. Although this phase was completed in 2001, its effects were not visible until the following year, when the temporary protective structure was unveiled.<ref name=Rtrot>{{cite web
|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CSTB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0F76257AA0191AB7&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420
|title=Repairing the ravages of time|accessdate=2009-01-24|date=2002-11-06|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Moffett, Nancy}}</ref> The repairs were expected to sustain the sculpture for about 30&ndash;50 years before any further repairs would be necessary.<ref name=ft/>

In 2003, the [[National Endowment for the Arts]] committed $250,000 to the Park District for the conservation and restoration of the reflecting pool.<ref>{{cite web
|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CTRB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0FF863B2310D6E10&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420
|title=Local groups to share $1.4&nbsp;million from NEA|accessdate=2009-01-24|date=2003-12-08|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=Chicago Tribune|author=Jones, Chris}}</ref> In 2004, the University of Chicago contributed $100,000 and the Park District Board $845,000 to repair the pool and its water circulation system.<ref>{{cite web
|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CSTB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=1024D04C45B29474&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420
|title=Supporters urge Park District to honor anarchist - Prof, labor activists testify in favor of naming lot for Parsons|accessdate=2009-01-24|date=2004-04-15|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Herrmann, Andrew}}</ref><ref>{{cite web
|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CTRB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=101F988C5C7285C0&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420
|title=Money flowing for museums - Park District raises Art Institute admission, OKs funding for sites |accessdate=2009-01-24|date=2004-04-15|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Dardick, Hal}}</ref> This work was  carried out in the summer of 2005 at a slightly reduced budget, and the fountain was filled with water for the first time in over fifty years.<ref name=HPlvfrf/><ref>{{cite web
|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CSTB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10AD989CC0D5035F&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420
|title=Money flows to rehab Fountain of Time pool |accessdate=2009-01-24|date=2005-06-08|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Herrmann, Andrew}}</ref>
In 2007, efforts began to add lighting. That same year the sculpture was nominated for the Chicagoland Initiative, a fund for the preservation of historic sites, backed by the National Trust for Historic Preservation and American Express. In a widely publicized contest that included [[wiktionary:open house|open house]] events where the public could tour and learn about the competing historic sites, $1&nbsp;million was available for preservation efforts in the [[Chicago metropolitan area]], but the fountain was not one of the 15 winning candidates.<ref name=HPlvfrf/><ref name=chic2>{{cite web|url=http://www.partnersinpreservation.org.php5-7.websitetestlink.com/chicago/index.php?sec=abt&locID=3|title=Chicagoland initiative|accessdate=2009-03-02|year=2009|publisher=Partners in preservation|publisher=[[National Trust for Historic Preservation|National Trust]] / [[American Express]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://press.nationaltrust.org/content/view/163/162/|title=American Express and The National Trust For Historic Preservation Launch Program in Chicago Metro Area: Community to Vote on 25 Historic Sites Announced as Candidates for "Partners in Preservation" Grants |accessdate=2009-03-24|date=2007-09-06|publisher=[[National Trust for Historic Preservation]]}}</ref>

